- **MFTLib.csproj:30** stale TODO references "GitHub Actions pipeline" — CI is Gitea Actions now and is set up. `ContinuousIntegrationBuild` is unconditionally `true` (correct for deterministic packs); just resolve/remove the comment.
- **Tag + push `v0.3.0`.** SourceLink (`PublishRepositoryUrl=true` + `SourceLink.GitHub`) resolves against github.com/mtschoen/MFTLib, so the exact packed commit AND the tag must be pushed to the GitHub mirror before `-t:Pack`, or source links 404.
- Already confirmed fine: 0.2.0 IS on NuGet; github.com/mtschoen/MFTLib exists (public); LICENSE.txt + README are packaged.

## Native C++ Cleanup (mft/mft_parse.cpp)

(Code moved out of `dllmain.cpp` into `mft/mft_parse.cpp` during the Linux-port refactor; line numbers in older notes are stale.)

- **[DONE] Parallelize path resolution**: The post-parse `ResolvePath` loop now fans out across `EffectiveThreadCount()` workers (same pattern as fixup+parse) when `numThreads > 1`, with a serial fallback. Read-only on `PathLookup`, independent output slots. Ranges are clamped with `std::min` so extra workers just get empty ranges (no thread-count-dependent branch to cover). Covered by `ParseFromFile_MultiThreaded_WithPaths_ResolvesPathEntries` (parallel) + the existing single-threaded test (serial).
- **[DONE] PathLookup silent name-drop**: `storeName` now bumps a `namesDropped` atomic on pool exhaustion; `ParseMFTImpl` surfaces it via `errorMessage` ("Path name pool exhausted; N names dropped, some paths truncated"). New `SetNamePoolCapacityOverride` test hook forces the branch (`ParseFromFile_NamePoolExhausted_ReportsTruncation`).

### Deferred — investigate later (not blocking 0.3)

- **Deduplicate ProcessRecordBatch / ProcessRecordSlice**: ~40 lines of shared attribute-scan logic. CAUTION: the two diverge in alloc-failure semantics — `ProcessRecordBatch` has `ShouldFailAlloc` + "entry array" error propagation, `ProcessRecordSlice` does a bare `realloc`. A wholesale merge (routing single-thread through the slice path) would change observable error behavior and break `ParseFromFile_SingleThreaded_AllocFailOnRealloc`. Safe form: extract only the shared per-record attribute walk into a helper, leave each function's alloc/error path intact. Cosmetic.
- **ResolvePath cycle detection**: O(depth^2) linear scan over `visited[128]`, but `depth` and `visitCount` are both capped at 128, so worst case is 128^2 per path and only for pathological 128-deep chains; the depth cap already guarantees termination. True O(1) needs a hash set keyed on uint64 record numbers. Low value vs risk — revisit only if path resolution shows up in a profile.
- **PathLookup over-allocation**: `namePoolCapacity = totalRecords * 64` bytes (~512 MB at 8M records). Avg filename is ~12-15 WCHAR, so a smaller multiplier would save memory — but now that exhaustion is surfaced (above) rather than silent, a blind reduction just trades memory for more truncated-path reports. Investigate a tuned multiplier (e.g. *32) paired with a pool-grow fallback, not a bare reduction.

## Review Follow-Ups

- Decide whether `MFTLib` should expose a higher-level scan-result contract for app-to-helper transport.
  Address by evaluating whether downstream apps should keep custom text formats for elevated scans or share a library-owned record serializer.

- Optional: make benchmark environment failures explicit instead of silently printing `Unknown`.
  Address by logging the WMI/CIM exception message or HRESULT in the benchmark header when system info queries fail.

## Test Infrastructure

- **Admin test runs hang on exit (recurring).** When `run-coverage.ps1` (full mode) or `native-coverage.ps1` is launched elevated via UAC, the elevated process intermittently fails to exit cleanly after `dotnet test` reports all tests passed — the parent shell sits indefinitely waiting on `Start-Process -Wait`. Same symptom appears with both `Microsoft.CodeCoverage.Console collect` (native script) and the plain coverlet path (managed script). Suspects to investigate:
  - **2026-05-28 confirmed — it is a real hang, not a missed UAC prompt.** The elevated `native-coverage-elevated.ps1` run launched (build + instrument + test-run-start all appeared in the elevated log, so UAC *was* approved), then `dotnet test` never returned within 300s. A watchdog killing the hung `dotnet`/`testhost` to escape produces a CORRUPT cobertura (normally-covered lines show uncovered; `collect` only finalizes on a clean child exit) — so kill-to-recover does not yield a usable report. Pragmatic verification meanwhile: run `scripts/native-coverage.ps1` NON-elevated — branch coverage stays 100%, only USN/admin lines drop; inspect the cobertura per-file to confirm changed lines are covered. See memory `reference_native_coverage_hang.md`. The split-admin-tests item below is the real remedy.
  - `WatchUsnJournal_*` admin tests use `CancelIoEx` to unblock a kernel wait — possible the cancel races with process teardown and leaves a worker thread in a non-signaled wait, blocking the runtime's exit. Worth checking with `procdump -ma` on a hung session to see what threads are alive.
  - `dotnet test` host process (`testhost.dll`) running under instrumentation may not flush the coverage file before the parent reaps it — could be the instrumentation harness, not the tests themselves.
  - A timeout wrapper around the elevated invocation (e.g. `Start-Process` with a watchdog that issues `taskkill /T` after N minutes past the last log line) would at least prevent the session from blocking forever.
  - Long-term: split admin-only tests into a separate test project so the non-admin run stays the default and elevated runs can be opted into with a known-stable test set.
